	abstract = {Environmental sources of variation influencing growth and reproduction performance of Kenya Boran cattle were evaluated using 4502 and 2681 growth and reproductive performance records from a large scale commercial ranch and a national beef research station located in the Arid and Semi Arid Lands of Kenya. Growth traits included birth (BW), weaning (WW), 12month (12W), 18month (18W) and 24month (24W) weights. Reproductive traits were age at first calving (AFC), pooled calving interval (CI) and CI in the first four parities (CI1, CI2 and CI3). Sex significantly affected all growth traits, parity of dam influenced BW, WW, 18W and 24W. Year-season effects significantly influenced BW, 12W, 18W and 24W. Age at weighing affected 12W, 24W and 18W. All CIs were significantly affected by year of calving. Herd-year-season of birth and calving, and AFC as a covariate were significant for AFC, CI1, CI2 and pooled CI. Mean estimates for BW, WW, 12W, 18W and 24W were 27.99kg, 184.55kg, 145.39kg, 178.82kg and 220.98kg, respectively. For AFC, CI1, CI2, CI3 and pooled CI, they were 1187.74days, 496.62days, 460.14days, 442.57days and 476.91days, respectively. This study shows environmental influence on both growth and reproductive performance of Kenya Boran cattle. Effective genetic improvement would therefore be feasible if these effects are well accounted for in genetic evaluation programmes.},
